To split up big JSON files locally in Node.js, you can follow these general steps:

1. Read the JSON file: Use the `fs` module to read the entire JSON file into memory.

```javascript
const fs = require('fs');

const filePath = 'path/to/big.json';

fs.readFile(filePath, (err, data) => {
  if (err) {
    console.error('Error reading JSON file:', err);
    return;
  }

  const jsonData = JSON.parse(data);
  // Continue with the splitting logic here
});
```

2. Determine how you want to split the JSON file: Decide on a splitting strategy that suits your specific requirements. For example, you can split based on the number of records, the size of individual parts, or any other criteria that makes sense for your use case.

3. Split the JSON data: Based on your splitting strategy, divide the JSON data into smaller parts. You can use JavaScript array methods (e.g., `slice()`, `splice()`) to extract subsets of the data.

```javascript
const chunkSize = 1000; // split into chunks of 1000 records

const chunks = [];
for (let i = 0; i < jsonData.length; i += chunkSize) {
  const chunk = jsonData.slice(i, i + chunkSize);
  chunks.push(chunk);
}

// Process each chunk separately (e.g., save to separate files, perform further processing, etc.)
chunks.forEach((chunk, index) => {
  const chunkFilePath = `path/to/chunk${index}.json`;
  fs.writeFile(chunkFilePath, JSON.stringify(chunk), (err) => {
    if (err) {
      console.error('Error writing chunk file:', err);
    } else {
      console.log(`Chunk ${index} saved successfully`);
    }
  });
});
```

In this example, we split the JSON data into chunks of 1000 records using the `slice()` method. Each chunk is then saved to a separate JSON file using the `fs.writeFile()` method.

4. Handle errors and process each chunk separately: Be sure to handle any errors that occur during the split and file-writing process. You can also perform any additional processing required for each individual chunk.

Note: The above example assumes that the JSON data is an array. Modify the splitting logic accordingly if your JSON data has a different structure.

Remember to replace `'path/to/big.json'` and `'path/to/chunk'` in the code with the appropriate file paths for your case.

